Moles of Fe extracted = 30 x 10⁶ g / 56 g/mol = 5.36 x 10⁵ mol;
Moles of PURE Fe₂O₃ reacted = 5.36 x 10⁵ mol / 2 = 2.68 x 10⁵ mol
Mass of PURE Fe₂O₃ = 2.68 x 10⁵ mol x 160 g/mol = 42.88 x 10⁶ g = 42.88 tonnes;
% purity of Fe₂O₃ = (42.88 tonnes / 100 tonnes) x 100 % = 42.88% ~ 42.9%;

Carbon dioxide = C;
Phosphorus pentoxide = B;
Both carbon dioxide and phosphorus pentoxide have simple molecular/covalent structures, meaning a small amount of energy is needed to overcome weak intermolecular forces. Their low melting points (C = -56 °C, B = 340 °C, both much lower than A, D, E) are consistent with this. Neither conducts electricity in solid state, also consistent with simple covalent structures. Phosphorus pentoxide (P4O10) is a larger molecule than carbon dioxide (CO2), hence it has stronger intermolecular forces and a higher melting point (B at 340 °C) compared to carbon dioxide (C at -56 °C).
